\begin{abstract}
In 2016, Dedre Gentner won the 'Turing Award' of Cognitive Science, i.e., the David E. Rumelhart Prize for Contributions to the Theoretical Foundations of Human Cognition, for her foundational work on Structural Mapping Theory (SMT). The theory describes how humans progressively discover relational abstractions across alignable objects; the studies that test and flesh out the theory span everything from attentional biases to key sensemaking activities like mental model formation and analogical transfer. <transition?> Gestalt principles of visual perception distill psychology theory and experimentation into concise descriptions of factors that influence how humans are likely to parse and understand a given 'scene', e.g., a bias towards connecting discrete elements based on continuity, proximity, or closure; designers consider these principles' predictions when creating interfaces. Following the Generative Theories of Interaction framework, we derive additional design principles that distill the knowledge of human cognition captured in SMT and suggest ways to operationalize it to help users quickly understand the relationships \textit{between} objects in the scene. These principles are validated by analyzing previous HCI and Visualization works' fulfillment or violations of these principles and how users were or were not able to use them for SMT-relevant tasks.
\end{abstract}

