\section{Introduction}

In an early paper on what was to become Structural Mapping Theory (SMT), \citet{} described how, perhaps counterintuitively, psychology studies predicted that humans can more easily list differences between two different mugs than between a mug and an alligator. Why? Especially when, objectively, a mug and an alligator are so much more different than two mugs! The punchline is that humans subconsciously look for latent structural mappings between objects that might be related; it can, for example, help them notice anomalies, like a subtle difference that distinguishes a poisonous mushroom from a nutritious one, and, perhaps most critically for abstract thought, learn abstractions from concrete examples and leverage those abstractions to parse and interpret new examples.

Prior work in user interface design for large (and small!) corpora, e.g., OverCode~\cite{}, Foobaz~\cite{}, Examplore~\cite{}, Exempla Gratis~\cite{}, ParaLib~\cite{}, MOCHA~\cite{}, PATAT~\cite{}, ``MesoText''~\cite{}, AbstractExplorer~\cite{}, and CorpusStudio~\cite{}, have implicitly or explicitly been designed to support this structural mapping process in users' minds when organizing and presenting piles of related objects. Some of these prior works have attempted to simulate the structural mapping process algorithmically and then present the pre-mapped results to users so that they do not have to mentally compose a mapping themselves. Others compute non-obvious abstract relationships between objects irrespective of how they fit together into a global mapping and modify objects' rendering to make the corresponding related components of objects more visually similar as well, with the hope that it will give users' mental 'structural mapping engines' (SMEs)~\cite{} a leg up. (Note that these and other strategies are not mutually exclusive.)

The core activity these systems enable---and the process of producing this work---are both dialectical activities~\cite{brewer}. \citet{dialecticalzhang} characterizes Brewer's concept of dialectical activities as repeated re-engagement that reveals value. For example, \citet{2025DTRAnnualLetter} characterizes research as just such a dialectical activity, i.e., ``re-examining a phenomenon intensely. [...] A process of looking at and continually reinterpreting a situation that we come to see it differently, and through which we build new understanding. It’s not so much about following a set of `scientific steps' as a means of producing something, as it is about looking at something repeatedly with unrelenting curiosity that eventually allows new understanding to emerge.''

Structural Mapping Theory describes an analogous largely subconscious process---at the level of human attention, perception, and cognition---where objects in relation to each other are parsed and re-parsed using different possible representations, mentally aligned and re-aligned using different local and global relational abstractions, drawing attention to the similarities and distinctions between aligned components across objects, possibly inspiring new more rich, latent, or generalizable mental representations and abstractions by which to align some or all of the related objects being considered.

This paper is also the result of repeated re-engagement: with our prior work, related work, and Structural Mapping Theory. Guided by the Generative Theories of Interaction (GToI) framework, we analyzed both the SMT literature and the empirical evidence from prior user studies of systems to compose principles for user interface design when users are going to see and reason about many related objects. Specifically, the second author assisted the first author in collecting and understanding both the formative and summative SMT literature and composing an initial set of principles. These principles were used by authors three through N to analyze prior works' fulfillment or violation of these principles, and its impact on users as captured by those works' evaluative user studies. Disagreements due to misunderstandings were used to clarify principles' descriptions while all other disagreements were used to refine the principles themselves and their expected domain of applicability.

In an age of our rapidly increasing ability to delegate to AI, this work attempts to capture how we can support human cognitive engagement with large and small collections of semi-structured data, and the benefits users reap when they do.

In summary, we contribute:
\begin{itemize}
    \item A concise description of Structural Mapping Theory, a key theory of human cognition, for the HCI community
    \item Theory- and empirically-backed principles for user interface design that support users' reasoning about many related objects
    \item An analysis of key past HCI papers with respect to these principles
    \item The demonstration of a process for deriving principles using the Generative Theories of Interaction framework \todo{see if other folks described their process}
\end{itemize}

