\section{SMT-Informed Extended Gestalt Principles}

\paragraph{Definitions}
In the description of these principles, we will use some common terms defined here:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Objects in a collection: the entities of which there are at least two; together they form a collection, e.g., code examples collected into a corpus~\cite{paralib}. %It could be the original objects in a collection, e.g., code examples collected into a corpus~\cite{paralib}, or it could be objects in a collection that have been transformed in some way, or it could be compound objects
    \item Structure: objects with structure can be broken down into \textit{components and relations between them}. For example, if the object is a sentence, it could be broken down into a sequence of text segments~\cite{abstractExplorer}. 'Sequence' describes the relationships between consecutive components, i.e., text segments. %Two clarifying anti-examples are: (1)
    The sentence could also be represented by a `bag of words', but that would be a structureless representation. %(2) The sentence could be described by a vector, e.g., in an embedding space. The vectors could themselves be considered transformed versions of the objects in a collection. %, but any interface that presents the vectors as objects would not translate into facilitating relational abstractions over the original sentences unless the transformation from sentences to vectors was structure-preserving and could be mapped back to the sentences easily---ideally perceptually.
    \item Components: %objects that have structure can be described by components and relationships between those components.
    Components of an object can have analogous components in other objects; that cross-object component mapping is determined by the alignment process in the user's mind and/or executed by the system algorithmicly.
    \item Relational Abstractions:
    
\end{enumerate}

Visual comparison can reveal the shared structure of objects in a collection.\todo{describe relationship to schema induction, mental modeling, learning, relational abstractions, etc.} The following principles facilitate this process.

\subsection{Collection level: Show the objects without abstracting away relevant structure.}
\todo{(Principle "-1")}
Any object structure that is abstracted away becomes impossible to form relational abstractions about.
%Without being able to see the objects, the structure of objects cannot be compared, and relational abstractions can not be composed.
For example, representing a collection of documents as dots in some scatter plot does not support the forming of relational abstractions across documents because the dot representation abstracts away the structure of the document it represents.

That said, relational abstractions inspired by similarities and differences between objects that are not both visible at the same time requires a sufficiently accurate memory of the currently unseen object to compare to; the relational abstractions that occur to the user may be limited by the (possibly evolving) mental representation of the unseen objects in memory. And objects that are never shown cannot influence the relational abstractions in their mind.
%While that vector is structured, representing the document as a dot in some 2-or-3D projection of that vector space is not a structured representation because the dot has no structure.

