\subsubsection{Artifact analysis}

\paragraph{Artifacts that fulfill this principle}

\textbf{Text Corpora} PaTAT~\cite{patat} and MOCHA~\cite{mocha} both show all the text in the collection being labeled in its entirety.
\textsc{ChainForge}~\cite{chainforge} fulfills this principle by showing the raw textual outputs of LLM queries. So do the grid and interleaved renderings of the LLM outputs grouped by Positional Diction Clustering in \citet{mesotext}. \textsc{Tempura}~\cite{tempura} fulfills this principle by showing all the raw textual queries made by search engine users. \todo{make sure it's all; fix it if it's not.}  \textsc{Serendyze}~\cite{serendyze} shows the entirety of the short texts in the corpus. %\todo{If Tempura and Serendyze don't both show all items in the corpus, does it only partially fulfill this principles? What if many are visible at once but not all?}
\textbf{Code Corpora}Both \textsc{Examplore}~\cite{examplore} and \textsc{ParaLib}~\cite{paralib} fulfill this principle by showing both all the code examples in the corpus in their entirety. (\textsc{Examplore} also shows all the code examples filtered to just include the structural components captured in the 'skeleton' abstraction that the system designers believed really mattered.) \textsc{OverCode}~\cite{overcode} showed the solutions to python programming problems in their entirety, modulo individual students' less common variable names and equivalent statement orders, and \textsc{Foobaz}~\cite{foobaz} re-expanded the abstracted away dimension of variable names, where all alternative student-chosen names for a particular variable role are visible.

