\subsubsection{Artifact critique: Artifacts that do and shouldn't or don't but should fulfill this principle}

\subsection{Component level: Compute and reify \textit{local} identity, relational, and/or conceptual matches.}
\todo{Principle 0a-c}

\paragraph{Elaboration on the wording of the principle itself}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textit{Local:} The intention of this prinicple is to support early steps in the alignment process illustrated in \Cref{fig:4-1}. However, since local identity, relational, and conceptual matches are computed without reasoning about possible global structural alignments, e.g., based on literal similarity alone, this can help Step 1 of users' internal SME's (\Cref{fig:4-1}) but also interfere with latter steps, e.g., Step 2 (\Cref{fig:4-1}) by getting in the way of identifying more latent structural similarities and differences if local matches between components that are not mapped to each other in any small submappings (kernels) cannot melt away or be selectively dismissed to allow for just focusing on matches between corresponding components within valid increasingly global submappings.
    \item \textit{Reify:} Display these local relationships such that their corresponding matches within other objects are clearest perceptually with the minimal possible additional cognition. Whether this is achieved is not dictated by any simple rule, e.g., unique visual variables for each relationship, but rather the intersection of multiple principles, as examples below may clarify.
\end{enumerate}

Identity matches are analogous to \texttt{===}, not \texttt{is} or \texttt{==}. In this analogy, the type coercion that \texttt{==} would impose before testing for equality suggests equating \texttt{My name is Harry} with \texttt{Harry is my name}. This would be too liberal a definition of an identity match: even thought the semantics are, in this case, unambiguously the same, the literal text is different. For natural language, this strict definition can, in general, preserve distinctions in meaning as well as stylistic distinctions and subtle differences in possible implied meanings. Legal contexts are where---to the untrained eye or large language model---subtle differences in language can result in significant differences in meaning, e.g., \texttt{will} versus \texttt{shall} as demonstrated in the Supreme Court ruling on IP agreements with universities~\cite{}. Word choices in news articles can have more sublte impacts on the understanding readers walk away with, e.g., whether a particular administration official or entity \texttt{labeled} or \texttt{determined} China a currency manipulator~\cite{triangulating}---the former suggests name-calling while the latter suggests some information-based decision process. The identical or even simply similar meaning of two or more sentences can be reified using common labels (Principle TBD).

In contrast, in programming languages where semantics are generally deterministic, identity matches can be relaxed by the system designer if, for example, they are designing for teachers and they confirm with their intended users that there is no pedagogical benefit to preserving the order of arguments to a communative operator such as \texttt{area = height*width} and \texttt{area = width*height}. Similarly, the first author would argue that, by default, \texttt{CO2} and \texttt{Carbon Dioxide} are not literally the same visual representation, and their identical semantic meaning can be reified as a 'common label' (principle tbd) but the system designer may determine that treating them like identity matches is better for the user, e.g., the cognitive and perceptual work for the task at hand is reduced or the particular cross-object relationships that the user wants to key in on are easier to notice.

\todo{note for ian: I've always wanted these abstractions to be able to be constructed by the user. reminds me of your notations stuff.}

For example, consider the following four sentences, with the visual variables of the text modified to reify pre-computed (overlapping) identity, relational, and conceptual matches:\\
\diffont{\colorbox{SkyBlue}{\textit{\textbf{M}ichael \textbf{J}ordan}}} \underline{is} \underline{a} \underline{basketball player}.\\
\diffont{\colorbox{SkyBlue}{\textit{\textbf{M}agic \textbf{J}ohnson}}} \underline{is} \underline{a} \underline{basketball player}.\\
An up-and-coming \underline{basketball player} \underline{is} \diffont{\colorbox{SkyBlue}{Victor Wembanyama}}.\\
Despite being tall, \diffont{\textit{Ari Ofsevit}} \underline{is} not \underline{a} \underline{basketball player}.\\

\texttt{Michael Jordan} and \texttt{Magic Johnson} are not identity matches at the token level; at the character level their leading characters are identity matches reified with text boldness. (If the system designer believes sub-token identity matches are helpful, they can reify them; otherwise they can stay at the level of comparing whole tokens. It is up to the system designer to assess what is most helpful to the user given the data and the task.) They, as well as Victor Wembanyama, are all basketball players though so they can be considered conceptual matches (here, reified via blue highlighting). The text segments \texttt{Michael Jordan} and \texttt{Magic Johnson} also have the same structural relationship to the rest of the object they are each a part of (the sentence)---so they are a relational match as well, reified via italicization).

The first author would argue that the text segments \texttt{Ari Ofsevit} shares the same structural relationship with the rest of its sentence, i.e., also the sentence subject in a subject-verb-object type of sentence, despite the fact that (1) the rest of the sentence being, content-wise, the opposite meaning of the rest of the sentences that \texttt{Michael Jordan} and \texttt{Magic Johnson} show up in and (2) the sentence \texttt{Ari Ofsevit} is in has an extra structure component: a leading dependent clause.

The \underline{is a basketball player} portions of the sentences are an identity match as well between the first two sentences; however, when considering the third sentence, it can make sense to break the component underline{is a basketball player} into multiple components, some of which are identity matches across all three sentences (\underline{is} and \underline{basketball player}) and some of which are only present as identity matches in the first two (\underline{is}, \underline{a}, and \underline{basketball player}). A continuous underline beneath \underline{is a basketball player} and \underline{basketball player is} could suggest an equivalence between them that does not help readers notice a missing word whose absence would change the meaning of the underlined portion.

Michael Jordan, Magic Johnson, Victor Wembanyama, and Ari Ofsevit are all people, so they are conceptual matches reified with a different font. In this example, the first, second, and fourth sentences have a clear structural mapping to each other (shared kernel)\todo{check usage of this term} while the third sentence, if we do not allow transformations of natural language sentences even if they are likely to perserve semantics, does not share the same structural mapping. As suggested by the eye-tracking study in AbstractExplorer~\cite{abstractExplorer}, reordering the sentences to group them by shared kernel would facilitate cross-document skimming amongst those willing to be guided by these pre-computed relationships rather than reading sentences one at a time in their entirety and comparing them cognitively. \todo{consider putting third sentence last} If re-ordering data by shared kernel so that such objects are aligned with each other (princple TBD) with no competing barriers (principle TBD) is not possible, allowing local matches that cross kernels to be dismissed can support folks in the cognitive process represented in \Cref{fig:4-1} rather than interfere with it with spurious local similarities. That said, calling these local matches regardless of whether or not there are possible alignments may facilitate the human discovering a different representation that makes it possible to align the objects, such that these local matches become matches between corresponding components.


\todo{add somewhere: in way that is more preferred, given typical and/or developed* human cognitive characteristics, and makes these local matches become matches between corresponding components... *experts may have developed structures, like those that enable master chess players to reason about chess moves at a higher level than individual pieces, that affect their preferences in a way that contradicts generic preferences for systematicity, etc.}

While the \texttt{M}'s, \texttt{J}'s, \texttt{is}'s, \texttt{a}'s, and \texttt{basketball player}'s are all identity matches, and the visual variables, i.e., text boldness and underlines, that denote the identity matches between the corresponding instances in the sentences are not unique, the first two sentence's parallel alignment with minimal oblique angles between the corresponding identical letters and words in the sentences (see Principle TBD) strongly suggests the correct mapping, i.e., from bold letters and underlined words in the first sentence to bold letters and underlined words in the second sentence, without requiring the human to search over possible mappings themselves, rather than simply perceiving the matches. Extending this correct mapping to the fourth sentence for the \texttt{is}'s, \texttt{a}'s, and \texttt{basketball player}'s is possibly slightly interfered with by the competing barrier, the third sentence (princple TBD). The local identity matches between the third sentence and the other three sentences, i.e., \underline{is} and \underline{basketball player}, require human visual search to perceive the mapping, though the simple fact that \underline{is} and \underline{basketball player} are underlined indicates that they are at least a local identity, relational or conceptual match to something else in the collection, which can therefore be known perceptually without search, though that knowledge does not directly help with the mental process these principles are designed to support: structurally mapping representations of objects in a collection to each other.

In an expanded example of the first two lines, we can superimpose reasoning about identity matches at the level of visual comparison of the literal text, and reason about the meaning of the text:\\
\textit{\colorbox{SkyBlue}{\textbf{M}ichael \textbf{J}ordan}} \underline{is a basketball player.} \pinkhighlight{Sam} \underline{likes \colorbox{SkyBlue}{him}}.\\
\textit{\colorbox{SkyBlue}{\textbf{M}agic \textbf{J}ohnson}} \underline{is a basketball player.} \pinkhighlight{Amy} \underline{likes \colorbox{SkyBlue}{him}}.\\
The blue and pink highlights call out two conceptual matches between the two lines, i.e., corresponding 'actors' \colorbox{SkyBlue}{\texttt{<Michael Jordan, Magic Johnson>}} and \pinkhighlight{\texttt{<Sam,Amy>}}, and extending the blue highlights to the textual references in the two lines (\colorbox{SkyBlue}{\texttt{<him, him>}}) in addition to using a visual variable that confirms the identical match between the \texttt{him}'s does turn what could be a cognitive computation into a perceptual one at both the literal and symbolic level.

This cognitive reading and comparison work is trivial (and barely worth doing) for two sentences, but across tens or hundreds of short documents (or more!), this can be crucial to not falling victim to wall of text-triggered disengagement. The same may be true of other data types at significant scales, but given that reading is not an innate skill but rather taught and text, unlike, for example, images, must be literally read and \textit{then} its meaning abstractly interpreted, the wall-of-text phenomenon can happen particularly quickly. Even if noticing commonalities and differences all the objects in a collection is not the conscious, stated goal of a given user, it is a pre-condition to common user goals, e.g., forming a mental model of the collection's contents.

\todo{see Toby's comment on this page in the Google Slides}

Note that, when computing and reifying local identity, relational, and/or conceptual matches across objects, the system designer will be implicitly defining what counts as an object if they do not do this explicitly. For example, the system designer can indicate relationships between the original objects, e.g., as shown above between two sentences; between transformations of the original objects, e.g., between programming statements with normalized argument orders for commutative operations; between objects about the original objects, e.g., between common bigrams extracted from a collection of documents; and between ``enhanced'' objects, e.g., objects whose representation has been expanded with metadata, like a prepended element indicating the sentiment of a sentence, as in Serendyze~\cite{serendyze}.\todo{consider moving}


